<p><strong>Sociology by Richard T. Schaefer 12th Edition PDF: Key Questions and Answers</strong></p>
<p><strong>1. Define sociology and its primary goals.</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p>Sociology is the scientific study of human society, social institutions, and social interactions. Its primary goals include describing, explaining, predicting, and changing social behavior.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>2. Explain the major theoretical perspectives in sociology.</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p>The three major theoretical perspectives are functionalism, conflict theory, and symbolic interactionism. Functionalism views society as a system of interconnected parts that work together for the benefit of the whole. Conflict theory focuses on the inequalities and power struggles within society. Symbolic interactionism examines how individuals interact with each other and how those interactions shape their social world.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>3. Discuss the importance of social stratification in society.</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p>Social stratification refers to the unequal distribution of power, wealth, and prestige in society. It creates social hierarchies and can have significant effects on individuals' life chances.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>4. Analyze the challenges facing contemporary societies.</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p>Contemporary societies face a wide range of challenges, including economic inequality, environmental degradation, global migration, and technological advancements. Sociologists study these issues to understand their causes and consequences and to develop solutions.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>5. Describe the role of research in sociology.</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p>Research is essential to the advancement of sociology. Sociologists use a variety of methods, such as surveys, interviews, and participant observation, to gather data about social phenomena. This data helps them develop and test theories and inform policy decisions.</p>
</blockquote>